## Release train (how version meets users)

Industry pattern: **trunk + release branch + tagged production** (used by Chrome, many mobile teams).

```
feature/* ──PR──► main (alpha) ──cut──► release/X.Y (beta) ──soak──► tag vX.Y.Z (production)
                      │                         │
                      └─ Firebase auto          └─ Play Closed Testing (X.Y.Z-beta)
```

| Stage | Branch / trigger | `version.name` bump? | User-facing string | End-user label |
|-------|------------------|----------------------|--------------------|----------------|
| **Alpha** | `main` push → `distribute-alpha` | No — same `X.Y.Z` until named release | `1.4.0-alpha` | **Alpha** |
| **Named release** | Manual `release` job on `main` | Yes — sets next `version.name` | `1.4.0` | Same; tags `v1.4.0` for bookkeeping |
| **Beta** | `release/X.Y` push | No — CI stamps `beta` only | `1.4.0-beta` | **Beta** |
| **Production** | `vX.Y.Z` tag | Already set | `1.4.0` | **Version 1.4.0** |
| **Hotfix** | `vX.Y.Z-hotfix.N` tag | PATCH semantics | `1.4.1` or `1.4.0-hotfix.1` | **Version 1.4.1** + what's new |

**Named release** (`release` job) is the **only** routine way to advance `version.name` on `main`. Merges alone do not bump.

