## End-user display rules (UX)

### Industry best practice

1. **Show one simple version** in account/settings (`1.4.0`) — not CI run numbers.
2. **Label prerelease channels plainly** — "Beta", "Early access", not internal jargon.
3. **Align [SemVer prerelease order](https://semver.org/#spec-item-11):** `alpha` < `beta` < `rc` < stable. Do not call beta builds "RC".
4. **Pair MINOR/MAJOR bumps with `distribution/whatsnew/`** — users infer importance from release notes, not only the number.
5. **Hotfixes:** prefer bumping PATCH (`1.4.0` → `1.4.1`) over exotic suffixes when Play Store allows; reserve `-hotfix.N` tags for git/traceability.

### Current app behaviour

| Build | Shown in app | Notes |
|-------|-------------|-------|
| Stable (production tag) | `Version 1.3.4` | Clean SemVer, no suffix |
| Beta (`release/**`) | `Version 1.3.4-beta` | CI stamps `beta` in-memory; `VERSION_NAME` includes suffix |
| Alpha (`main` / Firebase) | `Version 1.3.4-alpha` | CI stamps `alpha` in-memory; `VERSION_NAME` includes suffix |

All three tracks use the single `home_app_version` string key (`"Version %1$s"`). The prerelease suffix embedded in `VERSION_NAME` makes each track visually distinct. The old `home_app_version_rc` key (which incorrectly labelled beta as "RC") has been removed.

